super().__init__() calls the constructor (__init__ method) of the parent class, allowing a child class to inherit and initialize attributes from its parent. It ensures parent class setup runs, reducing code redundancy while enabling the child class to extend or add new functionality to its own initialization.

nn.Sequential: This acts as a container. Data will flow through the layers defined inside it in the exact order they are listed.

Inside the Sequential container (Layer 1):

	nn.Linear(input_dim, 512)
	This is a fully connected (dense) layer. It takes your input data (with a size of input_dim) and applies a linear transformation to output 512 features.

	nn.BatchNorm1d(512)
	Batch Normalization standardizes the outputs from the previous linear layer so they have a mean of 0 and a variance of 1. This helps the network train faster and remain stable. The 512 must match the output size of the previous layer.

	nn.ReLU()
	This is the activation function (Rectified Linear Unit). It introduces non-linearity into the network by taking any negative values and turning them into 0, while leaving positive values unchanged. This allows the network to learn complex patterns.

	nn.Dropout(dropout)
	This layer randomly "turns off" a percentage of the neurons (based on your dropout variable, defaulting to 40%) during each training pass. This forces the network to not rely too heavily on any single neuron, which heavily reduces overfitting and makes the model more robust.

