Training Hyperparameters
1. lr (Learning Rate = 0.001)
The learning rate dictates how big of a step the model takes when adjusting its internal weights to correct its mistakes.

Imagine you are blindfolded and trying to walk down to the lowest point of a valley (where the lowest point represents zero errors for your model):

If the lr is too high (taking giant leaps): You might completely step over the bottom of the valley and bounce back and forth on the hillsides. The model will fail to learn properly and become unstable.

If the lr is too low (taking baby steps): You will eventually reach the bottom, but it will take an incredibly long time. The model will train very slowly and might get stuck in a shallow, local dip instead of the true bottom of the valley.

1e-3 (or 0.001) is a widely accepted "Goldilocks" default value—not too big, not too small—that works well for many standard optimizers like Adam.

2. weight_decay (L2 Regularization = 0.0001)
Weight decay is a technique used to prevent overfitting. Overfitting happens when a model memorizes the training data perfectly but performs terribly on new, unseen data.

Weight decay stops this by slightly penalizing the model for having large internal weights:

How it works: During every training step, it slightly "decays" or shrinks the model's weights toward zero.

The result: It forces the model to distribute its learning across many different features rather than relying too heavily on just one or two specific features. This results in a "simpler," smoother model that generalizes better to real-world data.

1e-4 (or 0.0001) provides a very gentle downward pull on the weights, which is enough to keep them in check without destroying the model's ability to learn complex patterns.

The Leading Underscore (_) in a function name inside a class
In Python, naming a method with a single leading underscore (like _run_epoch) is a strong convention that means "this is for internal use only." It acts as a warning sign to other programmers using your code:

You shouldn't call trainer._run_epoch() directly from outside the class.

Instead, you would call a public method like trainer.train(), and that public method will handle calling _run_epoch behind the scenes.

While __init__() is a special method that runs exactly once when you first create an object, _run_epoch is a standard instance method that will likely be called many times throughout the lifecycle of the object.

